The '''Sacred Cod''' is a four-foot eleven-inch carved-wood [[effigy]] of an [[Atlantic cod]]fish, "painted to the life", hanging in the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|House of Represen{{shy}}ta{{shy}}tives]] chamber of Boston's [[Massachusetts State House|Massachu{{shy}}setts State House]]{{mdashb}}"a memorial of the importance of the [[cod fisheries|Cod-Fishery]] to the welfare of this Commonwealth"
(i.e. [[Massachusetts|Massachu{{shy}}setts]], of which cod is officially the "historic and contin{{shy}}u{{shy}}ing symbol").{{refn|
{{cite web |author= General Court of the Commonwealth of Massachu{{shy}}setts|work= Massachu{{shy}}setts General Law |url= http://www.mass.gov/legis/laws/mgl/2/2-13.htm |title= Ch. 2 §13 |publisher= General Court of the Commonwealth of Massachu{{shy}}setts |accessdate= January 15, 2013}}{{better source|reason=bare statute is primary source|date=March 2013}}
}}
The Sacred Cod has gone through as many as three incarnations over three centuries: the first
(if it really existed{{mdashb}}the authoritative source calling it a "prehistoric creature of tradition")
was lost in a 1747 fire; the second disappeared during the [[American Revolution]]; and the third is the one seen in the House today.

''Sacred Cod'' is not a formal name but a nickname which appeared in 1895, soon after the carving was termed "the sacred emblem" by a House committee appointed "to investigate the significance of the emblem [which] has kept its place under all administrations, and has looked upon outgoing and incoming legislative assemblies, for more than one hundred years".{{ran|C|p=3-4,12}}  Soon ''sacred cod'' was being used in reference to actual codfish as well, in recognition of the creature's role in building Massachu{{shy}}setts' prosperity and influence since early colonial times.

In 1933 the Sacred Cod was briefly "Cod-napped" by editors of the ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]'', prompting police to [[wikt:drag#English-search water|drag]] the [[Charles River]] and search an airplane landing in [[New Jersey]]. 
In 1968 it was taken briefly again, this time by students at the [[University of Massachusetts Boston|University of Massachu{{shy}}setts Boston]].

{{Anchor|Holy Mackerel}}A fish figure is displayed in the State House [[Massachusetts Senate|Senate]] chamber as well{{mdashb}}a [[brass]] casting (sometimes called the '''Holy Mackerel''') above its central chandelier.{{refn|
name="CIS"|{{cite web |url= http://www.sec.state.ma.us/cis/cismaf/mf3.htm |title= The Massachu{{shy}}setts State House Today |author= Citizen Information Service |publisher= Massachu{{shy}}setts Secretary of the Commonwealth |accessdate= April 8, 2009}}
}}

== Significance ==
[[File:Atlantic-cod-1.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1|{{center|A [[Atlantic cod|"sacred cod"]] in its {{nobreak|natural habitat}}}}]]
[[File:ColonyofNewHampshireSeal.png|thumb|right|upright=0.50|alt= a round seal with an upright fish on the left, a bundle of five arrows in the center, and a tree on the right|{{center|[[Seal of New Hampshire|Seal of New Hamp{{shy}}shire]], 1776}}]]
{{Quote box|align=center|salign=right
|{{nobr|Years before the statesmen of the}}<!--nobr forces text below image when window is narrow--> period had decided to make public {{shy|acknowl|edge|ment of the indebted|ness of the colony to the codfish, and had voted to adorn the assem|bly chamber with a wooden repre|sen|ta|tion thereof, indi|vid|uals and private cor|po|ra|tions were eager to pay tribute to the codfish, and vied with one another in their anxiety to make the recognition as conspicuous as possible.}}<!--p.34-->
|source = ''A History of the Emblem of the Codfish in the Hall of the House of Representatives. {{nowrap|Compiled by a Committee of the House.'' (1895)}}
}}
{{clear left}}
Codfishing was the first industry practiced by Europeans in Massachu{{shy}}setts, and it is said that the colony's first export was a cargo of fish.{{ran|C|p=23}}
Thus the codfish has been an important [[New England]] symbol for centuries, its image appearing on many early coins, stamps, corporate and government seals, and insignia such as the early crest of the ''[[Salem Gazette]]''.
In 1743 a prominent [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] businessman built a mansion in which "the end of every
stair in his spacious hall [displayed] a carved and gilded codfish."{{hsp}}{{ran|C|p=34{{hyphen}}36}}

In the late 1920s{{refn|{{cite web
|url=http://www.w-a.com/maplate.htm |title=Chris Woodcock's Massachusetts License Plates
}}{{better source|date=December 2014}}
}}
an "amusing" (as [[H. P. Lovecraft]] termed it){{refn | {{citation
|last=Lovecraft|first=H. P.|editor=Robert M. Price|title=The Whisperer in Darkness
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sxhiog7Y8EAC&pg=PA177|date=June 1, 2006
|publisher=Chaosium Inc.|isbn=978-1-56882-192-4|pages=177–8|work=The Hastur Cycle
}} }}
codfish emblem appeared briefly, "totem-like",{{refn|{{cite book
|author=Susanne K. Langer
|title=Philosophy in a New Key: A Study in the Symbolism of Reason, Rite, and Art
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TL4xbZojMh0C&pg=PA183
|date=2009|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-03994-0|p=183
}} }}
on Massachu{{shy}}setts license plates.
